Arsn’s Durnwss ov Onnronv nun Annnmwwmvv or Posrnv (5-10). Aper nevertheless declares that he will not hesitate to condemn Maternus’s neglect of oratory, and thereupon proceeds to expand upon the attractions of this profession. Nothing, he declares, is more useful, nothing more delightful, nothing more glorious than the career of the orator. In proof of this he refers to his own forensic triumphs, and points to the fame, the wealth,¹ and the power of Eprius Marcellus and Vibius Crispus, men high in the favor and counsels of the Emperor. Poetry, on the other hand, brings no positive advantage, its triumphs afford merely a passing pleasure, while the fame of even the greatest poet is much inferior to that of a gifted orator. Aper closes with an exhortation to Maternus to abandon poetry and devote himself to oratory, his earlier profession.
